//axhob_operation
{bust_knock}

NOTE: Probes the workload account's reachability via key-only SSH.
Used to confirm that a {burp_investiture}'s workload trust is currently
usable before dispatching real work, and used internally as the
final-step validation of {busn_garrison}.

//axhopt_typed_parameter
{burp_investiture}

//axhoq_precondition
A {burp_regime} profile exists at the given {burp_investiture} and its
referenced {burn_regime} profile is reachable.

//axhoq_precondition
{busn_garrison} has been run for this {burp_investiture} so that
{burc_workload_user} exists on the node and trusts the workload pubkey
derived from {burp_workload_key_file}.

//axhos_step
. *Open workload SSH*: connect as {burc_workload_user} using
{burp_workload_key_file}; key-auth only.

//axhos_step
. *Issue trivial command*: execute a no-op on the remote
(e.g., `true`) and observe the remote exit status.

//axhog_guarantee
No remote OS state was modified.

//axhoc_completion
Exit 0 when the remote command returns 0 within the probe window.
Non-zero on connection refusal, authentication failure, remote-exec
failure, or probe-window timeout.

//axhob_operation
{bust_command_file}

NOTE: Executes the contents of a local command file on the remote node
as {burc_workload_user} and captures stdout, stderr, and the remote
exit status to {burd_output_dir}.
The remote shell is whichever shell-letter garrisoned the node; the
operator does not choose it at dispatch time.

//axhopt_typed_parameter
{burp_investiture}

//axhopt_typed_parameter
{busi_scribed_command_file}

//axhoq_precondition
A {burp_regime} profile exists at the given {burp_investiture} and is
{bust_knock}-responsive.

//axhoq_precondition
The local command file referenced as the dispatch input exists and is
readable by the calling user.

//axhos_step
. *Open workload session*: open an SSH session to {burc_workload_user}
using {burp_workload_key_file}.

//axhos_step
. *Stream command file*: feed the command-file contents to the remote
shell.

//axhos_step
. *Capture outputs*: write remote stdout, stderr, and the remote exit
status to {burd_output_dir}.

//axhog_guarantee
The complete remote stdout, stderr, and exit code are durably written
under {burd_output_dir} regardless of the remote command's success or
failure.

//axhoc_completion
Exit 0 when dispatch and capture both complete (independent of the
remote exit code).
Non-zero on SSH connection failure, capture-write failure, or transport
interruption.

//axhob_operation
{bust_interactive_session}

NOTE: Opens an interactive SSH session to {burc_workload_user} on the
node named by a {burp_investiture}.
Foreground operation; control returns to the station shell when the
operator exits the remote shell.

//axhopt_typed_parameter
{burp_investiture}

//axhoq_precondition
A {burp_regime} profile exists at the given {burp_investiture} and is
{bust_knock}-responsive.

//axhos_step
. *Hand control to SSH*: invoke the local SSH client interactively
against {burc_workload_user} using {burp_workload_key_file}.

//axhos_step
. *Wait for exit*: block until the operator exits the remote shell.

//axhog_guarantee
No artifact is written to {burd_output_dir} — interactive sessions
deliberately bypass dispatch capture.
No local profile is modified.

//axhoc_completion
Exit code mirrors the SSH client's exit code when the session ends
normally.
Non-zero on connection or authentication failure before the session
opens.

//axhob_operation
{bust_garrison_bash}

NOTE: {busn_garrison} ceremony with native bash as the workload shell,
for Linux and macOS nodes.
Workload-only: garrison destroys any prior workload account named
{burc_workload_user}
and recreates it from a clean slate.
Garrison never reads or writes any `sshd_config` and never modifies
admin authorized_keys.

//axhopt_typed_parameter
{burp_investiture}

//axhoq_precondition
A {burp_regime} profile exists at the given {burp_investiture} and its
referenced {burn_regime} profile is reachable.

//axhoq_precondition
sshd is reachable on the node and {burp_privileged_user} authenticates
by key alone using {burp_privileged_key_file}. On Linux/Mac this
admin trust is operator-managed (e.g., placed via `ssh-copy-id`) —
there is no `busn_fenestrate` for non-Windows-OpenSSH nodes.

//axhoq_precondition
{burp_workload_key_file} is unencrypted and exists on the operator's
station.

//axhos_step
. *Open admin SSH*: connect as {burp_privileged_user} using
{burp_privileged_key_file}; key-auth only. Failure here surfaces a
missing or stale admin trust.

//axhos_step
. *Destroy workload*: remove any existing {burc_workload_user} account
via `userdel -r`.

//axhos_step
. *Create workload*: provision {burc_workload_user} as an unprivileged,
ssh-only account.

//axhos_step
. *Place workload trust*: write the workload pubkey
(derived via `ssh-keygen -y`) to the workload's authorized_keys with
the shell-letter `b` `command=` directive from {bujb_jurisdiction}.

//axhos_step
. *Plant workload key*: copy {burp_workload_key_file} to the workload
account at the shell-letter `b` destination path hardcoded in
{bujb_jurisdiction}.

//axhos_step
. *Validate round-trip*: SSH as workload, run a no-op command, verify
exit 0.

//axhog_guarantee
On success the node has exactly one workload account named
{burc_workload_user}, ssh-only, with both inbound (from operator) and
outbound (to GitHub or equivalent) key trust in place.

//axhoc_completion
Exit 0 when the round-trip validation succeeds.
Non-zero on admin SSH failure, account-management failure, key-write
failure, or workload validation failure.

//axhob_operation
{bust_garrison_cygwin}

NOTE: {busn_garrison} ceremony with Cygwin bash as the workload shell,
for Windows nodes reached via Cygwin sshd.
Workload-only: garrison destroys any prior workload account named
{burc_workload_user}
and recreates it from a clean slate.
Garrison never reads or writes any `sshd_config` and never modifies
admin authorized_keys; admin trust is established beforehand by
{busn_fenestrate}
on the Windows OpenSSH server, while Cygwin sshd hardening (if used
in addition to Windows OpenSSH) remains operator-manual.

//axhopt_typed_parameter
{burp_investiture}

//axhoq_precondition
A {burp_regime} profile exists at the given {burp_investiture} and its
referenced {burn_regime} profile is reachable.

//axhoq_precondition
{busn_fenestrate} has run for this {burp_investiture} so that
{burp_privileged_user} can authenticate by key alone using
{burp_privileged_key_file} (Windows OpenSSH path). Cygwin sshd is
installed on the node.

//axhoq_precondition
{burp_workload_key_file} is unencrypted and exists on the operator's
station.

//axhos_step
. *Open admin SSH*: connect as {burp_privileged_user} using
{burp_privileged_key_file}; key-auth only. Failure here surfaces a
missing or stale admin trust.

//axhos_step
. *Destroy workload*: remove any existing {burc_workload_user} Cygwin
account via the Cygwin user-management equivalent of `userdel -r`.

//axhos_step
. *Create workload*: provision {burc_workload_user} as an unprivileged,
ssh-only Cygwin account.

//axhos_step
. *Place workload trust*: write the workload pubkey
(derived via `ssh-keygen -y`) to the workload's authorized_keys with
the shell-letter `c` `command=` directive from {bujb_jurisdiction}.

//axhos_step
. *Plant workload key*: copy {burp_workload_key_file} to the workload
account at the shell-letter `c` destination path hardcoded in
{bujb_jurisdiction}.

//axhos_step
. *Validate round-trip*: SSH as workload, run a no-op command, verify
exit 0.

//axhog_guarantee
On success the node has exactly one workload account named
{burc_workload_user} reachable via Cygwin bash.

//axhoc_completion
Exit 0 when the round-trip validation succeeds.
Non-zero on admin SSH failure, Cygwin account-management failure,
key-write failure, or workload validation failure.

//axhob_operation
{bust_garrison_wsl}

NOTE: {busn_garrison} ceremony with WSL bash as the workload shell,
for Windows nodes reached via the WSL distribution `rbtww-main`
(hardcoded in {bujb_jurisdiction}).
Workload-only: garrison destroys any prior workload account named
{burc_workload_user}
and recreates it from a clean slate.
Garrison never reads or writes any `sshd_config` and never modifies
admin authorized_keys; admin trust is established beforehand by
{busn_fenestrate}
on the Windows OpenSSH server, while sshd hardening inside the WSL
distribution remains operator-manual.

//axhopt_typed_parameter
{burp_investiture}

//axhoq_precondition
A {burp_regime} profile exists at the given {burp_investiture} and its
referenced {burn_regime} profile is reachable.

//axhoq_precondition
The default WSL distribution on the node is `rbtww-main` and its sshd
is installed; mismatch fails fast with a clear error.

//axhoq_precondition
{busn_fenestrate} has run for this {burp_investiture} so that
{burp_privileged_user} can authenticate by key alone using
{burp_privileged_key_file} into the Windows OpenSSH host (used as the
admin entry point); the WSL session is then opened from that
foothold.

//axhoq_precondition
{burp_workload_key_file} is unencrypted and exists on the operator's
station.

//axhos_step
. *Open admin SSH*: connect as {burp_privileged_user} using
{burp_privileged_key_file}; key-auth only into the WSL distribution.
Failure here surfaces a missing or stale admin trust.

//axhos_step
. *Destroy workload*: remove any existing {burc_workload_user} account
inside the WSL distribution via `userdel -r`.

//axhos_step
. *Create workload*: provision {burc_workload_user} as an unprivileged,
ssh-only Linux account inside `rbtww-main`.

//axhos_step
. *Place workload trust*: write the workload pubkey
(derived via `ssh-keygen -y`) to the workload's authorized_keys with
the shell-letter `w` `command=` directive from {bujb_jurisdiction}.

//axhos_step
. *Plant workload key*: copy {burp_workload_key_file} to the workload
account at the shell-letter `w` destination path hardcoded in
{bujb_jurisdiction}.

//axhos_step
. *Validate round-trip*: SSH as workload, run a no-op command, verify
exit 0.

//axhog_guarantee
On success the node has exactly one workload account named
{burc_workload_user} reachable via the WSL distribution `rbtww-main`.

//axhoc_completion
Exit 0 when the round-trip validation succeeds.
Non-zero on WSL distribution mismatch, admin SSH failure, account-
management failure, key-write failure, or workload validation failure.

